* Caddy (https://github.com/caddyserver/caddy)
  Copyright the Caddy Authors.
  Licensed under the Apache License, Version 2.0.
  Stock Caddy 2 (no plugins) used as the ACME provider only. Binds
  :80 for HTTP-01 challenges; manages the TLS certificate for the
  operator's domain via Let's Encrypt; stores the cert in a shared
  Docker volume that sing-box reads. We chose Caddy here because
  its CertMagic-based ACME implementation is the most reliable in
  the Go ecosystem.

* sing-box (https://github.com/SagerNet/sing-box)
  Copyright SagerNet and contributors.
  Licensed under the GNU General Public License, Version 3.0.
  Actively-maintained Go reimplementation of the NaiveProxy server
  protocol with multi-user basic_auth, HTTP/3, and a clash-style
  management API for hot config reload. Reads its TLS certificate
  from the shared Caddy volume (Caddy does ACME, sing-box does
  TLS termination + the actual proxy). Bundled as a separate
  process / image; not statically linked with this proprietary
  code, so its GPL-3 stays scoped to its own image. Replaces the
  unmaintained klzgrad/forwardproxy plugin we depended on in
  v0.0.1.

* NaiveProxy (https://github.com/klzgrad/naiveproxy)
  Copyright klzgrad and contributors.
  Licensed under the BSD-3-Clause License.
  Historical client-side runtime from the pre-v0.4 server line. It is
  not bundled in the current VLESS+Reality server image.

* Laravel (https://github.com/laravel/laravel)
  Copyright Taylor Otwell.
  Licensed under the MIT License.
  Framework underlying the admin panel.

* Filament (https://github.com/filamentphp/filament)
